What is Termination Protection?

Termination protection prevents an EC2 instance from being accidentally terminated via the AWS Console, AWS CLI, or API.

It does not prevent:

Stopping the instance (unless stop protection is enabled)
Rebooting the instance
Termination due to Auto Scaling (in some scenarios)
Enable Termination Protection
aws ec2 modify-instance-attribute \
    --instance-id <INSTANCE_ID> \
    --disable-api-termination
Disable Termination Protection
aws ec2 modify-instance-attribute \
    --instance-id <INSTANCE_ID> \
    --no-disable-api-termination
Verify the Setting
aws ec2 describe-instance-attribute \
    --instance-id <INSTANCE_ID> \
    --attribute disableApiTermination

Example output:

{
    "DisableApiTermination": {
        "Value": true
    }
}
Find an Instance by Name Tag
aws ec2 describe-instances \
    --filters "Name=tag:Name,Values=datacenter-ec2" \
    --query "Reservations[].Instances[].InstanceId" \
    --output text
Common AWS CLI Workflow

Identify the instance:

aws ec2 describe-instances

Retrieve the instance ID:

aws ec2 describe-instances --filters ...

Modify the instance attribute:

aws ec2 modify-instance-attribute

Verify the change:

aws ec2 describe-instance-attribute
Interview Questions

Q1. Why would you enable termination protection?

Answer: To prevent accidental deletion of critical production EC2 instances by administrators or automation.

Q2. Does termination protection prevent stopping an instance?

Answer: No. It only blocks termination requests. Stopping an instance is controlled separately.

Q3. Which AWS CLI command enables termination protection?

aws ec2 modify-instance-attribute \
    --instance-id <INSTANCE_ID> \
    --disable-api-termination

Q4. How do you verify it is enabled?

aws ec2 describe-instance-attribute \
    --instance-id <INSTANCE_ID> \
    --attribute disableApiTermination

This is a common operational task for AWS administrators and DevOps engineers, especially in production environments.
